paragraphs.title: Introduction
paragraphs.text:
%md 

This notebook has been created having Scala as the standard programming language. 

But we still need to use %spark magic to have a spark context automatically created for us.

On the first notebook of this series, we took a look at the data model and we saw that there was a 
transactions table named *IRISDemo.BC_TRANSACTIONS* with two columns: *BC_TRANS_SRC_ACC* and *BC_TRANS_DEST_ACC*.

These columns point to tables *IRISDemo.BC_MERCH_ACCOUNT* and *IRISDemo.BC_CUST_ACCOUNT*. Let's try to build a
single data set with all this data joined so we can give a good look at the quality of our data:

paragraphs.title: Reading the data from IRIS
paragraphs.text:
%spark

val df = spark.read.iris("""select 
    c.BC_ACC_CUST_AGE as age,
    c.BC_ACC_CUST_GENDER as gender,
    t.BC_TRANS_AMOUNT as amount,
    t.BC_TRANS_IS_FRAUD as fraud,
    m.BC_MERCH_CODE as merchant,
    m.BC_MERCH_CATEGORY->BC_MERCH_CAT_CODE as category
from 
    IRISDemo.BC_TRANSACTIONS t, 
    IRISDemo.BC_MERCH_ACCOUNT m, 
    IRISDemo.BC_CUST_ACCOUNT c 
where 
    t.BC_TRANS_DEST_ACC=m.ID and 
    t.BC_TRANS_SRC_ACC=c.ID and 
    t.BC_TRANS_TYPE='PAYMENT'""")
    
df.cache()
df.count()

# 2 - Unbalanced data

msg.data: 2 - Unbalanced data

paragraphs.text:
%md

An unbalaced data set is problematic because training will be biased in favor of the dominant class (not fraud in this case). 
We will have to compensate for this later. 

A simple look at the number of frauds compared to genuine transactions is enough to see that this is a highly unbalanced data set.

# 5 - Basic Infrastructure

msg.data: 5 - Basic Infrastructure

paragraphs.title: Feature Selection - Testing for Independence
paragraphs.text:
%md

Feature selection is an important problem in Machine learning. There are many feature selection methods available such as mutual information, information gain, and chi square test.

We have 500K transactions. The *fraud* field will tell us if a transaction is marked as fraud or not. We have many features (age, gender, amount, merchant and category) but we are not
sure which features have an impact in *fraud* class. Given a feature X, we can use Chi Square Test to evaluate its importance to distinguish the class. 

By calculating the Chi square scores for all the features, we can rank the features by the chi square scores, then choose the top ranked features for model training. In other words, 
the higher value of the \chi^2 score, the more likelihood the feature is correlated with the class, thus it should be selected for model training.

The nice thing about Spark is that it can do all of this for us! We will use ChiSqSelector feature selector for that.

sure which features have an impact in fraud class. Given a feature X, we can use Chi Square Test to evaluate its importance to distinguish the class.

By calculating the Chi square scores for all the features, we can rank the features by the chi square scores, then choose the top ranked features for model training. In other words,
the higher value of the \chi^2 score, the more likelihood the feature is correlated with the class, thus it should be selected for model training.

The nice thing about Spark is that it can do all of this for us! We will use ChiSqSelector feature selector for that.

paragraphs.title: Vector Assembler
paragraphs.text:
%md

We need to transform our features in vectors before giving them to the ML algorithms. That is done by a class called VectorAssembler(). It will take an array of column names and will build a single column on our dataframe that will include all the selected features.

paragraphs.title: Vector Indexer
paragraphs.text:
%md

Spark needs to know if a feature is *categorical* or *numeric*. A categorical feature is something like Male/Female, Day of Week, a small range of numbers, etc. A numeric feature is a continuous value.

We could define this by hand but, again, Spark can help us with that with a VectorIndexer. It will look each feature and figure out for us if it is a categorical feature or continuous feature. We must give it a hint tough. Parameter MaxCategories defines the maximum number of items a feature must have to be considered a category. 

We have a merchant category. Let's see how many merchant categories do we have:
